
<h4>
    Algebraic Solutions
</h4>

<p class = 'directions'>
    A cannon fires a cannonball with a speed \( v_{x} \).
    The cannon is positioned on top of a cliff of height \( y_i \).
    The cannonball is in free-fall until it strikes the ground.
    Ignore the effects of air resistance.
    Consider the negative-y direction to be downward,
    and consider \( g \) to be the magnitude of free-fall acceleration.
    Consider the origin to be the point on the ground directly
    below the cannon, so that the initial horizontal position is zero.
</p>

<ul class = 'questionList'>
    <li class = 'question' data-answer = '\( \Delta t = \sqrt{\frac{2 y_i}{g}} \)'>
        Determine the time before the cannonball reaches
        the ground in terms of \( h \) and \( g \).
        Demonstrate that your answer is dimensionally correct.
    </li>
    <li class = 'question' data-answer = '\( \Delta x = v_x \sqrt{\frac{2 y_i}{g}} \)'>
        Determine the horizontal displacement of the cannonball
        before it reaches the ground in terms of \( h \), \( g \), and \( v_{x} \).
        Demonstrate that your answer is dimensionally correct.
    </li>
</ul>

