<h4>
    Function with trigonometry
</h4>


<p class = 'directions'>
    Position, velocity, and acceleration are all vectors,
    meaning that they have both magnitude and direction.
    Vectors can be written in two different forms,
    component form and magnitude-direction form.
    The solutions you derived above are in component form,
    in which you found an individual number for the horizontal
    and vertical dimensions of a vector. In these problems,
    you will derive the magnitude-direction form of one vector,
    the velocity. You can practice the math <a href = '/pod/dynamics/two_dimensional_dynamics/vector_form_conversion'>here</a>.
</p>

<ol class = 'questionList'>
    <li class = 'question' data-answer = '\( v(t) = \sqrt{v_x^2 + g^2 t^2} \)'>
        Derive a function for the speed (magnitude of velocity)
        of the cannonball \( v(t) \).
    </li>
    <li class = 'question' data-answer = '\( \theta(t) =  \tan^{-1} \left( \frac{gt}{v_x} \right) \text{ degrees below the +x axis.}\)'>
        Derive a function for the direction of the cannonball's
        velocity \( \theta(t) \), in terms of degrees below the positive-x-axis.
    </li>
</ol>


